00:51:04.736 --> 00:51:09.736
Make lots of plots and do that kind of behavior to make sure they don't do it wrong.

00:51:09.736 --> 00:51:10.736
Yeah.

00:51:10.736 --> 00:51:11.736
Yeah, do you...

00:51:11.736 --> 00:51:13.736
I'm so curious if y'all have advice for...

00:51:13.736 --> 00:51:19.736
I actually just talked to a person who's planning, like, curriculum for high school students who are learning...

00:51:19.736 --> 00:51:24.736
They were gonna learn, like, Python and to deploy web apps and things like that.

00:51:24.736 --> 00:51:27.736
And I think originally they were gonna do a lot of, like, teaching.

00:51:27.736 --> 00:51:30.736
Like, building up what they need to know.

00:51:31.736 --> 00:51:36.736
And now they're trying to figure out, like, to what degree should we pull AI in really early?

00:51:36.736 --> 00:51:40.736
And get you, say, like, deploying something first.

00:51:40.736 --> 00:51:43.736
They're asking, like, how should we sequence the instruction?

00:51:43.736 --> 00:51:46.736
Do you have thoughts on that?

00:51:46.736 --> 00:51:49.736
I think, like, half a year ago, I basically gave myself permission.

00:51:49.736 --> 00:51:52.736
Like, okay, let's see if you can actually vibe code two apps from scratch.

00:51:52.736 --> 00:51:54.736
You're not gonna look at the code whatsoever.

00:51:54.736 --> 00:51:56.736
See what happens.

00:51:56.736 --> 00:51:58.736
And then eventually I did start looking at the code.

00:51:58.736 --> 00:52:00.736
But two things happened.

00:52:00.736 --> 00:52:02.736
First thing that happened was I was using Flask.

00:52:02.736 --> 00:52:05.736
And there was no CSRF protection anywhere.

00:52:05.736 --> 00:52:11.736
It does kind of feel like you should at least manually do the exercise of what could go wrong if you don't add that.

00:52:11.736 --> 00:52:13.736
Like, there's something about reading from...

00:52:13.736 --> 00:52:15.736
There's something about, like, book smarts.

00:52:15.736 --> 00:52:16.736
You read from a book.

00:52:16.736 --> 00:52:17.736
And there's something about street smarts.

00:52:17.736 --> 00:52:21.736
Like, oh, I've actually pwned someone's server because there was no CSRF protection on the thing.

00:52:21.736 --> 00:52:22.736
Right?

00:52:22.736 --> 00:52:23.736
And I don't know.

00:52:23.736 --> 00:52:24.736
Like, something...

00:52:24.736 --> 00:52:27.736
I do think, like, that sniff test, something about that.

00:52:27.736 --> 00:52:30.736
It's kind of like doing a physics experiment.

00:52:30.736 --> 00:52:35.736
Something with the Bunsen burner and the professor making something explode is making it stick way more in your mind.

00:52:35.736 --> 00:52:37.736
Again, something about the story.

00:52:37.736 --> 00:52:41.736
And just reading it from, like, a text that goes by so fast.

00:52:41.736 --> 00:52:43.736
Like, an LLM can barf paragraphs.

00:52:43.736 --> 00:52:44.736
Right?

00:52:44.736 --> 00:52:46.736
I fear that you're just not gonna...

00:52:46.736 --> 00:52:48.736
It's not gonna be in your noggin as much.

00:52:48.736 --> 00:52:51.736
So one thing I think could be cool is that you could say, like, okay, kids.

00:52:51.736 --> 00:52:52.736
We're all gonna build a web app now.

00:52:52.736 --> 00:52:54.736
