00:52:54.736 --> 00:52:56.736
Then we're gonna see if we can break it.

00:52:56.736 --> 00:52:59.736
And, you know, that that might be the classroom activity.

00:52:59.736 --> 00:53:02.736
But you're also confronted with, like, the unhappy path, maybe.

00:53:02.736 --> 00:53:03.736
Something like that.

00:53:03.736 --> 00:53:09.736
The other thing that went wrong, by the way, with the LLM doing the vibe coding thingy is I told it to make a make file and to, like, test stuff.

00:53:09.736 --> 00:53:12.736
And there was, like, a production database.

00:53:12.736 --> 00:53:16.736
But every time that I would do unit testing, it would flush the production database.

00:53:17.736 --> 00:53:23.736
Because it forgot to set this one environment variable to only use a local SQLite thing as opposed to the thing in production.

00:53:23.736 --> 00:53:25.736
So my flashcards kept getting removed.

00:53:25.736 --> 00:53:31.736
Again, I do think if you hit your head, and that's part of the curriculum, that could definitely be useful.

00:53:31.736 --> 00:53:32.736
Right?

00:53:32.736 --> 00:53:33.736
But I don't know.

00:53:33.736 --> 00:53:38.736
If you're reading about an environment variable and going through the pain and knowing how things can go wrong.

00:53:39.736 --> 00:53:48.736
How do you get people to be good at correcting the LLM if you've never done a correction on yourself before?

00:53:48.736 --> 00:53:50.736
That's the tricky bit, I think.

00:53:50.736 --> 00:53:52.736
Because that's the skill we're gonna care about.

00:53:52.736 --> 00:53:54.736
Like, writing the code is becoming less valuable.

00:53:54.736 --> 00:53:59.736
But being able to check the code or being able to improve a code base by glancing at it.

00:53:59.736 --> 00:54:01.736
That's a more impressive skill these days.

00:54:01.736 --> 00:54:04.736
But how do you train that without the aforementioned part?

00:54:05.736 --> 00:54:08.736
I think right now we're seeing this rapid adoption of coding agents.

00:54:08.736 --> 00:54:15.736
And everyone's using Cloud Code and Gemini and OpenCode and all the things.

00:54:15.736 --> 00:54:21.736
But I've noticed that a lot of people are essentially putting their minds to sleep a little bit.

00:54:21.736 --> 00:54:28.736
And that they feel like the agent knows what it's doing and is looking out for doing things the right way.

00:54:29.736 --> 00:54:33.736
The more you use these things, you observe over and over that they have egregious blind spots.

00:54:33.736 --> 00:54:35.736
And they forget to do things.

00:54:35.736 --> 00:54:38.736
They will blow away a production database by accident.

00:54:38.736 --> 00:54:44.736
And so I feel like probably at some point in the future, maybe there'll be some evolved version of coding agents.

00:54:44.736 --> 00:54:51.736
Where there's an agentic supervisor in the loop that's applying software engineering best practices.

00:54:51.736 --> 00:54:54.736
And security guidelines and all those things.

00:54:54.736 --> 00:54:58.736
But I think right now it's a little bit of a do-it-yourself affair.

00:54:58.736 --> 00:55:05.736
Either you create a process where you essentially apply this supervision.

00:55:05.736 --> 00:55:10.736
Where either you're the supervisor, which is more or less the best case scenario.

00:55:10.736 --> 00:55:13.736
Is that you're the supervisor and you actually know what questions to ask.

00:55:13.736 --> 00:55:17.736
How to correct the LLM and tell it, oh you forgot to...

00:55:17.736 --> 00:55:22.736
You're putting the production database in the same place as the application deployment.

00:55:22.736 --> 00:55:24.736
You're going to destroy that with your next rsync.

00:55:24.736 --> 00:55:26.736
Don't do that.

00:55:26.736 --> 00:55:28.736
I actually had that happen to me by the way.

00:55:28.736 --> 00:55:30.736
Unfortunately it was data that didn't really matter.

00:55:30.736 --> 00:55:33.736
Where I was like, did you just destroy my production database with that rsync?

00:55:33.736 --> 00:55:36.736
Yeah you did. You didn't think twice about doing it either.

00:55:36.736 --> 00:55:39.736
Did you just rmrf that directory?

00:55:39.736 --> 00:55:41.736
That had important stuff in it.

00:55:41.736 --> 00:55:46.736
And so there's a lack of guardrails right now.

00:55:46.736 --> 00:55:48.736
And supervision.

00:55:49.736 --> 00:55:54.736
And so that's probably why we're seeing disproportionate benefit to coding agents.

00:55:54.736 --> 00:55:56.736
To really experienced people.

00:55:56.736 --> 00:56:00.736
Because they're able to leverage their pre-existing skills.

00:56:00.736 --> 00:56:07.736
And bring their judgment and ability to recognize when the agents are going off the rails.

00:56:07.736 --> 00:56:11.736
And if you don't have that experience or the ability to recognize.

00:56:11.736 --> 00:56:13.736
Oh no, press escape, you're doing the wrong thing.

00:56:13.736 --> 00:56:15.736
You've gone off the rails.

00:56:16.736 --> 00:56:20.736
Then for a lot of people they're just going to be in a world of pain.

00:56:20.736 --> 00:56:24.736
I think for, all this is reminding me.

00:56:24.736 --> 00:56:27.736
For a web app you could maybe come up with a really constrained web framework.

00:56:27.736 --> 00:56:30.736
Where there's only one way to deploy this thing.

00:56:30.736 --> 00:56:32.736
And that's the full proof LLM proof.

00:56:32.736 --> 00:56:35.736
Because it's a CRUD app you can really constrain it.

00:56:35.736 --> 00:56:37.736
For data science though.

00:56:37.736 --> 00:56:41.736
The whole point is that you are able to be creative I think.

00:56:42.736 --> 00:56:45.736
Like mixing matching tools in ways that wasn't sort of.

00:56:49.736 --> 00:56:52.736
Weirdest trick that works in data science.

00:56:52.736 --> 00:56:53.736
Weirdest trick.

00:56:53.736 --> 00:56:55.736
Back when I was at Probable.

00:56:55.736 --> 00:56:59.736
I was able to, I figured out a way to get logistic regression to beat XGBoost.

00:56:59.736 --> 00:57:03.736
The way that I did that is you got to imagine there's a data set with cars.

00:57:03.736 --> 00:57:06.736
So year that it was built, color, brand.

00:57:06.736 --> 00:57:07.736
That kind of data set.

00:57:07.736 --> 00:57:09.736
And then price.

00:57:09.736 --> 00:57:10.736
I want to predict the price.

00:57:10.736 --> 00:57:12.736
Second hand car.

00:57:12.736 --> 00:57:14.736
So okay.

00:57:14.736 --> 00:57:17.736
What you could do is you could sort of say let's do one hot encoding.

00:57:17.736 --> 00:57:19.736
So like car brands like one, lots of zeros.

00:57:19.736 --> 00:57:21.736
And like colors like lots of zeros.

00:57:21.736 --> 00:57:23.736
And one somewhere, one hot encoded.

00:57:23.736 --> 00:57:25.736
And then what you can do is you could sort of try and do a distance.

00:57:25.736 --> 00:57:28.736
Between two different encodings of these cars.

00:57:28.736 --> 00:57:30.736
But the problem is.

00:57:30.736 --> 00:57:32.736
How are you going to compare two colors?

00:57:32.736 --> 00:57:35.736
That distance is always going to be one basically.

00:57:35.736 --> 00:57:36.736
Because it's a different color.

00:57:37.736 --> 00:57:38.736
Okay.

00:57:38.736 --> 00:57:40.736
How are you going to do a similarity lookup?

00:57:40.736 --> 00:57:41.736
Okay.

00:57:41.736 --> 00:57:44.736
What you could do is you could have like a regression model.

00:57:44.736 --> 00:57:45.736
So you're going to take your encoding.

00:57:45.736 --> 00:57:48.736
And then you're going to train towards the price variable.

00:57:48.736 --> 00:57:51.736
Oh and that means that you have a coefficient for every single variable.

00:57:51.736 --> 00:57:54.736
Which includes like the one that was for a specific car brand.

00:57:54.736 --> 00:57:56.736
Let's say.

00:57:56.736 --> 00:57:58.736
Oh actually that can be an embedding technique now.

00:57:58.736 --> 00:58:00.736
You can take your linear model.

00:58:00.736 --> 00:58:02.736
And then we can use those coefficients.

00:58:02.736 --> 00:58:04.736
Multiply that by the original array.

00:58:04.736 --> 00:58:07.736
Oh and if you then want to do a k nearest neighbor kind of a thing.

00:58:07.736 --> 00:58:10.736
Then you now have a system that gets like a distribution of prices.

00:58:10.736 --> 00:58:11.736
Based on similar cars as well.

00:58:11.736 --> 00:58:14.736
And similarity now is not just how similar are the properties.

00:58:14.736 --> 00:58:16.736
But also how does that relate to the price.

00:58:16.736 --> 00:58:18.736
And it turned out that if you build a system that way.

00:58:18.736 --> 00:58:20.736
That you actually got better predictions than XGBoost.

00:58:20.736 --> 00:58:23.736
And you also got like an uncertainty bound around that as well.

00:58:23.736 --> 00:58:24.736
Okay.

00:58:24.736 --> 00:58:25.736
I like this freedom.

00:58:25.736 --> 00:58:28.736
Like this is something that no textbook will tell you.

00:58:28.736 --> 00:58:30.736
But if you start thinking about the problem a bit more and more.

00:58:30.736 --> 00:58:33.736
Then you can come up with these super duper creative solutions.

00:58:34.736 --> 00:58:37.736
And that's also kind of feedback I do want to give to people.

00:58:37.736 --> 00:58:38.736
Because people have always been asking me.

00:58:38.736 --> 00:58:41.736
Like Vincent what book do you read to come up with these techniques?

00:58:41.736 --> 00:58:43.736
And I think the whole point is that I don't.

00:58:43.736 --> 00:58:45.736
Like I just take a step back.

00:58:45.736 --> 00:58:46.736
I take pen and paper.

00:58:46.736 --> 00:58:47.736
I have a coffee.

00:58:47.736 --> 00:58:49.736
And I think about the problem.

00:58:49.736 --> 00:58:51.736
Far away from social media and distractions.

00:58:51.736 --> 00:58:55.736
And I give myself permission to let my mind free.

00:58:55.736 --> 00:58:57.736
And it's a little bit easier now that I've got a kid actually.

00:58:57.736 --> 00:58:59.736
Because he really gets me right from the laptop.

00:58:59.736 --> 00:59:01.736
He really wants to go to the playground.

00:59:01.736 --> 00:59:03.736
But that's how you do it.

00:59:03.736 --> 00:59:06.736
And again, but the problem though is like if you want to then have LLMs help you.

00:59:06.736 --> 00:59:08.736
And LLMs are super powerful.

00:59:08.736 --> 00:59:11.736
It is very tempting to be intellectually lazy.

00:59:11.736 --> 00:59:13.736
And that's when you should kind of resist.

00:59:13.736 --> 00:59:16.736
And maybe like this was a tweet from Andrej Karpathy.

00:59:16.736 --> 00:59:18.736
Like I think a couple of years ago.

00:59:18.736 --> 00:59:20.736
Maybe if learning feels a bit painful.

00:59:20.736 --> 00:59:21.736
Maybe that's a good thing.

00:59:21.736 --> 00:59:23.736
Because it means that you're doing something that's uncomfortable.

00:59:23.736 --> 00:59:25.736
And you're doing something that's a little bit unknown.

00:59:25.736 --> 00:59:27.736
And if you look back at your week.

00:59:27.736 --> 00:59:29.736
And you kind of go like this entire week was easy peasy.

00:59:30.736 --> 00:59:32.736
Maybe you should start getting worried.

00:59:32.736 --> 00:59:34.736
I think that's maybe a way to think about it.

00:59:34.736 --> 00:59:36.736
Because then maybe you should invest in a new hobby.

00:59:36.736 --> 00:59:38.736
And learn a new skill maybe that way.

00:59:38.736 --> 00:59:40.736
Maybe I'm doing calculus again just for the fun of it.

00:59:40.736 --> 00:59:42.736
Also for the puzzling.

00:59:42.736 --> 00:59:44.736
Part of the whole point of learning is like mental.

00:59:44.736 --> 00:59:46.736
It's like mental exercise.

00:59:46.736 --> 00:59:48.736
Like I did pure math as an undergrad.

00:59:48.736 --> 00:59:51.736
And so I spent a lot of time like doing you know analysis.

00:59:51.736 --> 00:59:54.736
And topology and abstract algebra.

00:59:54.736 --> 00:59:55.736
And things like that.

00:59:55.736 --> 00:59:57.736
I think like you know.

00:59:57.736 --> 00:59:59.736
Certainly like I don't apply any of those skills now.

00:59:59.736 --> 01:00:03.736
Like was it useful to learn Galois theory?

01:00:03.736 --> 01:00:05.736
Like I did.

01:00:05.736 --> 01:00:07.736
But I've forgotten all of it.

01:00:07.736 --> 01:00:10.736
But I do think that like mental stretching.

01:00:10.736 --> 01:00:12.736
And like racking your brain really hard.

01:00:12.736 --> 01:00:15.736
To think about difficult theoretical problems.

01:00:15.736 --> 01:00:19.736
And being able to reason about like these abstract structures in your mind.

01:00:19.736 --> 01:00:21.736
Like it does you know.

01:00:22.354 --> 01:00:28.594
Again, I don't know how I would have turned out if I hadn't done theoretical math,

01:00:28.594 --> 01:00:34.194
but I would like to believe that it had some practical benefit in my current existence where

01:00:34.194 --> 01:00:39.794
I'm basically doing software engineering and not doing any pen and paper math.

01:00:41.474 --> 01:00:46.034
So I did operations research, so definitely a different field of math, but the thing with

01:00:46.034 --> 01:00:51.153
operations research is you've got to prove that your mathematical allocation is optimal.

01:00:51.714 --> 01:00:56.594
If it's not optimal, you can't prove it, it's wrong, basically. It's a thing that the professor

01:00:56.594 --> 01:01:00.514
really hard drilled into me. And something about that is a critical attitude. Like,

01:01:00.514 --> 01:01:03.473
I'm not going to believe anything anyone says, I want to see the full proof.

01:01:03.473 --> 01:01:07.153
And maybe it's not so much the theory, but more the attitude that comes with the science,

01:01:07.153 --> 01:01:09.473
I like to think, that also makes you good at debugging.

01:01:10.609 --> 01:01:14.609
Hypothesizing a bit, but I can definitely imagine, Wes, that that's a thing that's still stuck with you.

01:01:15.609 --> 01:01:22.609
This kind of reminds me of the paper, or at least the title of the paper. It's called Better To Be Frustrated Than To Be Bored,

01:01:22.609 --> 01:01:29.609
about effective states students might have, and which ones are better for learning.

01:01:29.609 --> 01:01:37.609
And I do think what you described is, you know, like writing it out isn't necessarily boredom, but like frustration,

01:01:37.609 --> 01:01:45.609
or kind of responding to something and wanting to prove something or lock it down. That does strike me as kind of a key.

01:01:45.609 --> 01:01:52.609
I have a kid now, so I can tell you this story. My theory right now is kids learn to speak because they're frustrated,

01:01:52.609 --> 01:01:58.609
because they have an idea in their mind they can't tell their parents. And there's this god-awful phase with a lot of screaming in the household.

01:01:58.609 --> 01:02:03.609
When the kid is making it absolutely sure that something is highly amiss, but eventually the kid learns,

01:02:03.609 --> 01:02:06.609
oh, I got to learn the language, and that's how I can properly communicate to my parents.

01:02:06.609 --> 01:02:09.609
There's a little frustration thing there that I do think is key.

01:02:10.609 --> 01:02:17.609
Hadley, bringing it back to you. I know you've brought up things like I've seen, I think, in the Posit Slack.

01:02:17.609 --> 01:02:24.609
I think you shared out an article that mentions you wouldn't bring a forklift to the gym.

01:02:25.609 --> 01:02:33.609
I'm curious your thoughts on this topic of people putting in effort and learning. How do you see it?

01:02:37.609 --> 01:02:48.609
I think the one thing that's really interesting is many of us now have the opportunity to automate parts of our job that we love doing.

01:02:49.609 --> 01:02:57.609
You can automate that, and you can find joy in different parts of your job, but you also don't necessarily have to.

01:02:57.609 --> 01:03:03.609
You still can keep doing those bits. Maybe not all the time, but tactically.

01:03:03.609 --> 01:03:08.609
You don't have to just optimize for velocity all the time.

01:03:09.609 --> 01:03:15.609
But then the other thing I think about is why does anyone learn to play a musical instrument?

01:03:16.609 --> 01:03:24.609
You can find someone on YouTube or Spotify or Apple Music doing a way better job of playing any music than you.

01:03:24.609 --> 01:03:32.609
There's also some of these skills we gain joy from, regardless of whether we're the best at the world or not.

01:03:32.609 --> 01:03:36.609
And I think some of that, how do we teach this stuff?

01:03:37.609 --> 01:03:44.609
Coming back to when you do math in high school, most of that you're never going to use.

01:03:44.609 --> 01:03:57.609
But you're training your brain in this cool problem-solving way that you can get a lot of enjoyment from, independent of the strict utility.

01:03:58.609 --> 01:04:01.609
And again, if I can come back to a notebook.

01:04:01.609 --> 01:04:07.609
One thing I really like about notebooks, it is a nice place where you can put your thoughts as well.

01:04:07.609 --> 01:04:13.609
There's something about a notebook that is able to do that way more than a code base.

01:04:14.609 --> 01:04:16.609
As an artifact, so to say.

01:04:17.609 --> 01:04:21.609
It definitely does feel a little bit more like a thing you would write down in your own little diary,

01:04:21.609 --> 01:04:26.609
as opposed to a theoretical book in the closet somewhere.

01:04:26.609 --> 01:04:28.609
It can still be very personal.

01:04:28.609 --> 01:04:32.609
And you can also just research something that you're interested in, as opposed to something for your work.

01:04:33.609 --> 01:04:36.609
I will say, with LLMs though, this is a habit.

01:04:37.609 --> 01:04:42.609
Even if I generate notebooks from scratch and I try to go super big and stuff,

01:04:42.609 --> 01:04:47.609
you can still vibe code defensively, if that makes sense, in a notebook.

01:04:47.609 --> 01:04:50.609
I have a video on this on the Marimo channel, if people are interested.

01:04:50.609 --> 01:04:53.609
But one thing I really love to do now is, if I make charts,

01:04:54.609 --> 01:04:59.609
the use case here is, I wanted to find out if buying a bread machine was going to save the family money.

01:04:59.609 --> 01:05:01.609
It's a really silly use case.

01:05:01.609 --> 01:05:05.609
But you can imagine there's this one line going up that says,

01:05:05.609 --> 01:05:07.609
how much money do I spend going to the bakery?

01:05:07.609 --> 01:05:10.609
And there's this other line going up that's a little bit more flat that says,

01:05:10.609 --> 01:05:14.609
I only pay for the ingredients and I have this upfront cost of the bread maker.

01:05:14.609 --> 01:05:16.609
And those two lines intersect somewhere.

01:05:16.609 --> 01:05:19.609
Except I'm a Bayesian, so it's not a break-even point.

01:05:19.609 --> 01:05:22.609
It's a break-even distribution because both lines, they wiggle around a bit.

01:05:22.609 --> 01:05:23.609
There's a bit of uncertainty.

01:05:23.609 --> 01:05:26.609
We got to take that into account as well, right?

01:05:26.609 --> 01:05:30.609
So I was interested in the break-even point distribution.

01:05:30.609 --> 01:05:34.609
But one thing I explicitly told Claude to do, and I did it wrong a few times,

01:05:34.609 --> 01:05:35.609
and I kept hammering on it.

01:05:35.609 --> 01:05:39.609
Those two charts need to have the same x-axis and they have to be on top of each other.

01:05:39.609 --> 01:05:41.609
Because otherwise, I cannot mix.

01:05:41.609 --> 01:05:45.609
Otherwise, I cannot glance at both distributions at the same time.

01:05:45.609 --> 01:05:48.609
And when Claude was done, I noticed that it was way off

01:05:48.609 --> 01:05:51.609
because the distribution at the bottom did not fit the chart on top.

01:05:51.609 --> 01:05:53.609
You can just sort of draw straight lines.

01:05:53.609 --> 01:05:55.609
You can see it was really wrong.

01:05:55.609 --> 01:05:57.609
But the only reason I was able to find that bug

01:05:57.609 --> 01:05:59.609
was because I was coding defensively, quote-unquote.

01:05:59.609 --> 01:06:02.609
Those two charts have to be under each other.

01:06:02.609 --> 01:06:03.609
And there have to be all sorts of sliders,

01:06:03.609 --> 01:06:06.609
so I can also wiggle around to check my intuition.

01:06:06.609 --> 01:06:08.609
But I am very conscious of the fact that I have to sort of

01:06:08.609 --> 01:06:10.609
code defensively in a notebook these days,

01:06:10.609 --> 01:06:14.609
especially if I go for more than two cells that Claude can just go ahead and rip.

01:06:14.609 --> 01:06:17.609
And that's also, again, still a bit of a mental exercise.

01:06:17.609 --> 01:06:19.609
You got to think about that upfront.

01:06:19.609 --> 01:06:21.609
If you're not doing the syntax,

01:06:21.609 --> 01:06:22.609
oh, how am I going to model this?

01:06:22.609 --> 01:06:24.609
What do I care about figuring that out?

01:06:24.609 --> 01:06:26.609
Yeah.

01:06:26.609 --> 01:06:28.609
Don't skip that.

01:06:28.609 --> 01:06:31.609
I think the visualization is super interesting, though,

01:06:31.609 --> 01:06:36.609
because I think that's a completely different lens to look at your effort.

01:06:36.609 --> 01:06:38.609
And whenever you look at things through a different lens,

01:06:38.609 --> 01:06:41.609
you're more likely to find problems.

01:06:41.609 --> 01:06:43.609
And I've been kind of sort of wondering about that

01:06:43.609 --> 01:06:47.609
in the era of reviewing LLM-generated code.

01:06:47.609 --> 01:06:53.609
Sure, you probably don't want to read every single line of code the LLM has written.

01:06:53.609 --> 01:06:55.609
That's not super valuable.

01:06:55.609 --> 01:06:57.609
But it feels like tools to be like,

01:06:57.609 --> 01:07:00.609
okay, let's change the code set this way.

01:07:00.609 --> 01:07:03.609
There's now a new big blob of code here.

01:07:03.609 --> 01:07:06.609
So you can be like, well, actually, kind of structurally,

01:07:06.609 --> 01:07:08.609
that doesn't feel right to me.

01:07:08.609 --> 01:07:12.609
I expected the blob to be over here or to be spread out this way.

01:07:12.609 --> 01:07:15.609
So it feels like, I don't know,

01:07:15.609 --> 01:07:19.609
maybe there's a scope for kind of cool new visualization tools

01:07:19.609 --> 01:07:23.609
to help us understand what LLM is doing to our code.

01:07:23.609 --> 01:07:26.609
In the same way that looking at pictures of data is so useful

01:07:26.609 --> 01:07:30.609
if we can figure out new abstractions for visualizing code

01:07:30.609 --> 01:07:35.609
so we can better understand what was the big picture implication of this change.

01:07:35.609 --> 01:07:38.609
Another sort of just mental exercise that I do recommend people do,

01:07:38.609 --> 01:07:42.609
and this is like an old school thing people never really did.

01:07:42.609 --> 01:07:44.609
You know how you win a Kaggle competition?

01:07:44.609 --> 01:07:46.609
By checking the training data set

01:07:46.609 --> 01:07:48.609
to see if there's any mislabeled items in there.

01:07:48.609 --> 01:07:50.609
It's a little thing that tends to go wrong.

01:07:50.609 --> 01:07:53.609
There's a lot of Kaggle competitions with bad labels.

01:07:53.609 --> 01:07:55.609
And again, like, how do you find out?

01:07:55.609 --> 01:07:58.609
Well, just look at the data set for a bit.

01:07:58.609 --> 01:08:00.609
And it's one of these steps that people sometimes miss.

01:08:00.609 --> 01:08:03.609
And visualizations can make that a whole lot simpler.

01:08:03.609 --> 01:08:05.609
Maybe you do something with an embedding,

01:08:05.609 --> 01:08:06.609
and then the sentiment curves,

01:08:06.609 --> 01:08:08.609
and there's all sorts of fun stuff you can do.

01:08:08.609 --> 01:08:11.609
But again, there's all these exercises that

01:08:11.609 --> 01:08:12.609
if you go just a little bit slower,

01:08:12.609 --> 01:08:14.609
you can just give yourself permission to like,

01:08:14.609 --> 01:08:15.609
just do this one little check.

01:08:15.609 --> 01:08:18.609
And oh boy, does that really help you understand stuff as well.

01:08:18.609 --> 01:08:21.609
And again, human in the loop.

01:08:21.609 --> 01:08:24.609
Even if you're a business that like,

01:08:24.609 --> 01:08:25.609
there's this dream that you can have like

01:08:25.609 --> 01:08:28.609
the one man billionaire startup with LLMs now and stuff, right?

01:08:28.609 --> 01:08:30.609
But something is telling me if you're the one man

01:08:30.609 --> 01:08:31.609
and the LLM does everything,

01:08:31.609 --> 01:08:34.609
and you have no idea what the LLM is doing,

01:08:34.609 --> 01:08:35.609
like, really?

01:08:35.609 --> 01:08:37.609
One billion company?

01:08:37.609 --> 01:08:40.609
Is that the, really?

01:08:40.609 --> 01:08:41.609
I don't know.

01:08:41.609 --> 01:08:42.609
There's still something about like,

01:08:42.609 --> 01:08:44.609
there's gotta be some human around

01:08:44.609 --> 01:08:45.609
that still understands what's happening.

01:08:45.609 --> 01:08:47.609
I think that's still kind of fine.

01:08:47.609 --> 01:08:49.609
The joke I always make is natural intelligence

01:08:49.609 --> 01:08:52.609
is also still a pretty good idea.

01:08:52.609 --> 01:08:53.609
Yeah.

01:08:53.609 --> 01:08:54.609
Wes, do you,

01:08:54.609 --> 01:08:55.609
I feel like there was a response,

01:08:55.609 --> 01:08:57.609
kind of a reaction from you.

01:08:57.609 --> 01:08:59.609
Do you think a person will

01:08:59.609 --> 01:09:02.609
vibe code a billion dollar company?

01:09:02.609 --> 01:09:04.609
If they don't get too distracted

01:09:04.609 --> 01:09:06.609
by shiny objects along the way,

01:09:06.609 --> 01:09:08.609
that seems to be the thing that's,

01:09:08.609 --> 01:09:10.609
the thing that's happening.

01:09:10.609 --> 01:09:13.609
I mean, I've been observing things like Gastown

01:09:13.609 --> 01:09:15.609
and things from the Steve Yegi-verse.

01:09:15.609 --> 01:09:17.609
And honestly, my reaction,

01:09:17.609 --> 01:09:19.609
and this is a little bit of a hot take,

01:09:19.609 --> 01:09:20.609
is like,

01:09:20.609 --> 01:09:21.609
I'm like,

01:09:21.609 --> 01:09:23.609
are any of these people building anything useful?

01:09:23.609 --> 01:09:24.609
I'm like,

01:09:24.609 --> 01:09:26.609
show me something that I can use that's useful.

01:09:26.609 --> 01:09:27.609
I can't,

01:09:27.609 --> 01:09:28.609
I'm not,

01:09:28.609 --> 01:09:29.609
I mean, I see that there's a lot of work being done.

01:09:29.609 --> 01:09:30.609
A lot of tokens are being burned,

01:09:30.609 --> 01:09:34.609
but I'm not seeing the useful output.

01:09:34.609 --> 01:09:36.609
I wrote a blog post called

01:09:36.609 --> 01:09:38.609
The Mythical Agent Month

01:09:38.609 --> 01:09:39.609
that's been circulating.

01:09:39.609 --> 01:09:41.609
And that came out a couple of weeks ago.

01:09:41.609 --> 01:09:42.609
And the idea,

01:09:42.609 --> 01:09:43.609
yeah,

01:09:43.609 --> 01:09:44.609
and so the idea is that,

01:09:44.609 --> 01:09:45.609
that,

01:09:45.609 --> 01:09:46.609
you know,

01:09:46.609 --> 01:09:47.609
this,

01:09:47.609 --> 01:09:49.609
the Mythical Man Month is a book that came out in 1975.

01:09:49.609 --> 01:09:50.609
So over 50 years ago.

01:09:50.609 --> 01:09:52.609
And obviously software engineering and computers

01:09:52.609 --> 01:09:53.609
and the whole,

01:09:53.609 --> 01:09:54.609
the internet is,

01:09:54.609 --> 01:09:56.609
a lot of stuff has happened in the last 50 years.

01:09:56.609 --> 01:09:59.609
But Fred Brooks wrote a bunch of claims,

01:09:59.609 --> 01:10:00.609
you know,

01:10:00.609 --> 01:10:01.609
essentially the core idea is that

01:10:01.609 --> 01:10:03.609
when you add people to a project,

01:10:03.609 --> 01:10:05.609
to a late project,

01:10:05.609 --> 01:10:06.609
it will become later.

01:10:06.609 --> 01:10:07.609
And that the larger a team is,

01:10:07.609 --> 01:10:09.609
the more communication overhead,

01:10:09.609 --> 01:10:10.609
coordination overhead you have.

01:10:10.609 --> 01:10:12.609
And so essentially now with,

01:10:12.609 --> 01:10:13.609
with agents doing the development,

01:10:13.609 --> 01:10:14.609
more or less,

01:10:14.609 --> 01:10:17.609
you have like an agentic version of the Mythical Man Month,

01:10:17.609 --> 01:10:18.609
where,

01:10:18.609 --> 01:10:19.609
you know,

01:10:19.609 --> 01:10:21.609
essentially like you were the chief surgeon.

01:10:21.609 --> 01:10:24.609
And so you have to have this conceptual model of how the system works

01:10:24.609 --> 01:10:25.609
and what the agents are supposed to do.

01:10:25.609 --> 01:10:28.609
But you also have to review and supervise their work

01:10:28.609 --> 01:10:29.609
and make sure they're doing the right thing.

01:10:29.609 --> 01:10:33.609
And they aren't creating giant messes for each other to clean up.

01:10:33.609 --> 01:10:34.609
And so,

01:10:34.609 --> 01:10:36.609
for what I'm seeing is that people are creating these,

01:10:36.609 --> 01:10:37.609
like half million line,

01:10:37.609 --> 01:10:38.609
you know,

01:10:38.609 --> 01:10:39.609
million line software projects,

01:10:39.609 --> 01:10:42.609
but they're just gigantic hairballs that are like,

01:10:42.609 --> 01:10:43.609
at the end of the day,

01:10:43.609 --> 01:10:44.609
like,

01:10:44.609 --> 01:10:45.609
you know,

01:10:45.609 --> 01:10:47.609
this could have been 50,000 lines of code and a great deal,

01:10:47.609 --> 01:10:48.609
simpler resource,

01:10:48.609 --> 01:10:49.609
less,

01:10:49.609 --> 01:10:50.609
you know,

01:10:50.609 --> 01:10:51.609
more resource efficient,

01:10:51.609 --> 01:10:52.609
like in a lot more,

01:10:52.609 --> 01:10:54.609
a lot more useful and without lots of like unnecessary features,

01:10:54.609 --> 01:10:56.609
because there's nobody to say,

01:10:56.609 --> 01:10:57.609
no,

01:10:57.609 --> 01:10:58.609
you can add a hundred additional features.

01:10:58.609 --> 01:11:00.609
Like every day you wake up and over your morning coffee,

01:11:00.609 --> 01:11:01.609
you're like,

01:11:01.609 --> 01:11:02.609
oh,

01:11:02.609 --> 01:11:03.609
can you add these five new features that I had?

01:11:03.609 --> 01:11:04.609
I thought of,

01:11:04.609 --> 01:11:05.609
you know,

01:11:05.609 --> 01:11:06.609
a hundred more.

01:11:06.609 --> 01:11:07.609
And the agent's never going to say no.

01:11:07.609 --> 01:11:11.609
And the agents won't refactor the code and make the code cleaner.

01:11:11.609 --> 01:11:12.609
Unless you,

01:11:12.609 --> 01:11:13.609
unless you tell them to.

01:11:13.609 --> 01:11:14.609
And so it's,

01:11:14.609 --> 01:11:15.609
it's essentially like.

01:11:15.609 --> 01:11:18.609
Now like your human,

01:11:18.609 --> 01:11:23.609
like your judgment and your taste as a designer of these software systems

01:11:23.609 --> 01:11:25.609
has become the most single,

01:11:25.609 --> 01:11:28.609
most important skill and you're in your tool belt.

01:11:28.609 --> 01:11:32.609
And unless you are extremely judicious about what you build and what you

01:11:32.609 --> 01:11:38.609
don't build and how you proactively hold the agents accountable to build in

01:11:38.609 --> 01:11:39.609
accordance with your vision.

01:11:39.609 --> 01:11:40.609
And to not,

01:11:40.609 --> 01:11:43.609
if they create messes that you spot the messes and you clean them up.

01:11:43.609 --> 01:11:47.609
But essentially like it's created a new type of industrial process for,

01:11:47.609 --> 01:11:49.609
for building software.

01:11:49.609 --> 01:11:52.609
And there's a lot of people that are just kind of Yoloing it with their

01:11:52.609 --> 01:11:56.609
agent sessions and going in and essentially they're asking a thousand prompts

01:11:56.609 --> 01:11:57.609
in a row,

01:11:57.609 --> 01:12:01.609
like requesting one feature after another and they're spotting bugs and asking

01:12:01.609 --> 01:12:02.609
the agents to fix them.

01:12:02.609 --> 01:12:05.609
But with little regard for the types of code bases that they're,

01:12:05.609 --> 01:12:07.609
that they're generating.

01:12:07.609 --> 01:12:12.609
And I think people who are engaging in that motor are in for a world of pain

01:12:12.609 --> 01:12:16.609
at some point in the future when they hit the inevitable scalability wall,

